:: III. The Rába
“I tell this one badly,” the old man says after a long silence, his fingers resting against the empty porcelain cup as though he has forgotten it is there. 
“Every time I speak of it, something feels wrong, as though memory itself refuses to stay still long enough to become a proper story.” Still, he continues.
In 1681 he joined the army of the Holy Roman Emperor, not because he dreamed of glory but because he wanted to see the borderlands for himself, the violent 
edges where empires pressed against each other like grinding stone. “A library cannot show you that kind of world,” he says quietly. “A horse can.” Two years 
later, in 1683, while the Ottoman army marched toward Vienna, Marsili found himself far from the famous siege itself in a smaller battle along 
the river Rába in Hungary, a skirmish history barely remembers but one he never escaped in memory. What he recalls most is not strategy or 
heroism but confusion: dust thick enough to blind, shouting so close it no longer sounded human, the crushing weight of a horse collapsing onto him, 
and the freezing shock of river water against his side. “I remember thinking only one thing,” he says softly. “So this is how it ends. I was twenty-five years old.”

He explains that battle did not resemble paintings or songs; it was chaos so complete that survival often depended more on chance than skill. 
Men shouted in languages he barely understood, horses screamed louder than soldiers, and for moments at a time he could not even tell 
whether he was alive or dying. But he survived for one simple reason: the men who found him did not kill him. They were Crimean Tartar riders
fighting for the Ottoman forces, and even beneath blood and mud they recognized he was a gentleman. To them, a noble prisoner was valuable,
“a coin yet to be spent,” as Marsili calls it. One of the riders lifted his chin and examined his face carefully, not cruelly but with the detached attention 
of someone inspecting cloth in a market before deciding its worth, and in that moment Marsili understood something terrible—that count, scholar, 
and young nobleman from Bologna no longer meant anything. “On the banks of the Rába,” he says quietly, “I stopped being Marsili of Bologna and became merchandise.”

