:: V. Invisible Things
“The Pasha of Temesvar made me a servant,” the old man says, “though the word itself is far too small for what it meant.” Before his capture, 
Marsili had spent his entire life being served by others. Servants dressed him, brought him water, cleaned his rooms, prepared his meals, and carried
out tasks so ordinary that he barely noticed them. Then, almost overnight, his world reversed completely. He became the one pouring drinks, carrying supplies, 
cleaning filth, obeying orders, and performing tasks he admits he would rather not describe aloud. “It was humiliating,” he says plainly,
“but humiliation was not the important part.” The pasha beat him sometimes for mistakes, sometimes for nothing at all except exhaustion or anger,
yet Marsili speaks of it with surprising calmness. “I have seen worse cruelty done with worse intention,” he says quietly. “And I have lived too long 
to lie about suffering just to make myself sound brave.”

What stayed with him most was not the pain but what he learned while becoming almost invisible inside the Ottoman camp. 
Servants, he explains, see the parts of power that diplomats and nobles never notice. They hear arguments between officers, learn which leaders ar
e feared or respected, watch soldiers prepare before dawn, and witness what powerful men reveal when they believe nobody important is listening. 
“Diplomats see thrones,” Marsili says. “Servants see reality.” Because he poured coffee and remained silent, people stopped noticing him entirely, 
and in that invisibility he discovered how much information powerful men reveal in front of those they consider beneath them. The old man leans forward
slightly, pale eyes fixed on yours. “If you are ever near powerful people,” he says softly, “be quiet. Be useful. Listen more than you speak. 
You will learn more in one hour than they will learn in a lifetime.”

